SIMPLE: parquet
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Parquet
<hw>Par*quet"</hw> <pr>(p⟦aum⟧r*k⟦amac⟧" or p⟦aum⟧r*k⟦ecr⟧t")</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. See <er>Parquetry</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A body of seats on the floor of a music hall or
theater nearest the orchestra; but commonly applied to the whole lower
floor of a theater, from the orchestra to the dress circle; the
pit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Same as <er>Parquetry</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>In various European public bourses, the railed-in
space within which the ⟦ldquo⟧agents de change,⟦rdquo⟧ or privileged
brokers, conduct business; also, the business conducted by them; --
distinguished from the <contr>coulisse</contr>, or outside
market.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>In most European countries, the branch of the
administrative government which is charged with the prevention,
investigation, and punishment of crime, representing the public and not
the individual injured.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Parquetage</ent>⟦br⟧
